title: "writing-a-mesh-protocol-in-ltl"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-05
abstract: We'll build a LoRa mesh routing protocol entirely in Lateralus, covering packet framing, AODV route discovery, and why binary primitives simplify the implementation.

# Introduction

The LoRa network is a popular choice for low-power wide-area networking. However, its inherent complexity often leads to custom implementations of routing protocols. In this article, we'll demonstrate how to build a basic LoRa mesh routing protocol using only Lateralus. Our approach relies on binary primitives, which provide an efficient and concise way to express complex algorithms.

## Packet Framing

In a LoRa network, packets are transmitted over the air and must be received and forwarded correctly to maintain connectivity. The standard LoRa packet format consists of a header, payload, and trailer.

packet = struct {
    header: bytes(3),
    payload: uint16,
    trailer: uint8
}

This structure can be defined in Lateralus as a single `struct` with three fields. By using binary primitives, we've eliminated the need for explicit type definitions or boilerplate code.

## AODV Route Discovery

AODV (Ad-hoc On-Demand Distance Vector) is a popular routing algorithm used in wireless networks. It works by maintaining a distance vector that indicates the minimum hop count from each node to every other node. When a new node joins the network, it initializes its distance vector and sends it to neighboring nodes. Upon receiving a distance update, a node adjusts its own distance vector accordingly.

In Lateralus, AODV route discovery can be implemented using a combination of `map` operations and bitwise arithmetic.

function route_discovery(node_id: int, neighbor_id: int) -> map {
    var distance_vector = map{}
    // Initialize distance vector
